        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>546 Nth 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> st.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr A. Huebsch<lb/>
                Revd and dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Possibly&#44; you may not have<lb/> seen the <hi rend="underline">Jewish Record</hi> of last Friday.  In<lb/> a communication by Mr I. Rubenstein&#44; you have<lb/> been chosen umpire to decide whether Maimonide&#39;s<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; is a defence of his belief in a bodily<lb/> resurrection&#44; or a denial of that article of faith.<lb/></p>
            <p>I maintain that the author endeavours throughout to<lb/> show that he does not confound &#91;Hebrew&#93; with &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and<lb/> that though dwelling at large on the subject of the<lb/> former&#44; because agreeable to reason&#44; he unequivocally<lb/> accepts the doctrine of a resuscitation after death&#44; or<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; as within the scope of God&#39;s illimitable<lb/> powers.  Mr Rubenstein&#44; on the contrary&#44;<lb/> maintains that Maimonides declares the doctrine<lb/> of the resurrection absurd.  He further represents<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; as denying the authenticity of the book of<lb/> Daniel&#44; and I maintain that Maimonides uses it<lb/> as a support to the aforenamed doctrine.<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Mr Rubenstein intimates that Maimonides<lb/> ridicules the idea that the prayers <del>embodying</del> containing the<lb/> acknowledgment of a bodily resurrection were composed<lb/> by the ancient Sages&#44; or &#91;Hebrew&#93;; I hold that<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; wishes to prove the universal acceptance of the<lb/> doctrine by pointing to those very prayers.<lb/></p>
            <p>In the event of your consenting to act in the capacity<lb/> of umpire&#44; it will be necessary for you to know<lb/> that I base my convictions upon the translation of<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">Maamar</hi> by Samuel Ibn Tibon&#44; as published<lb/> in 5410 at Amsterdam by Joseph Attias.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours respectfully<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia August 31<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 1879<lb/></p>
                
            <p>PS. Your answer will be inserted in the <hi rend="underline">Jewish Record</hi>&#44;<lb/> the office of which is 614 Chestnut st.<lb/></p>
        </body>
